<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1266,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1341,1367]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Within the 
<emphasis box="[468,564,1341,1366]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">sticticus</emphasis>
-complex, this species belongs to a group of taxa with well-defined black spots. Among this group it combines a blackened clypeus, metasternal process with posterior angle higher than postero-lateral angles, apical notch of the fifth ventrite with bifid tooth (
<figureCitation box="[1070,1143,1416,1442]" captionStart="FIGURE 4 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox="[165,1420,916,1441]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,882,1474]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4 – 6. Ventral details of Berosus degallieri. 4) Mesosternal process,; 5) Metasternal process; 6) Fifth ventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195950/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[1126,1143,1416,1442]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
), extensive metafemoral pubescence, a long basal piece compared with total length of male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1071,1144,1453,1479]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,838,862]" captionTargetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[488,1100,309,815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Berosus degallieri (0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[1128,1144,1453,1479]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), parameres and median lobe about the same length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="55" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1266,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1527,1553]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[358,467,1528,1554]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Holotype</typeStatus>
(male). Total body length: 
<quantity box="[791,884,1528,1554]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
; maximal width: 
<quantity box="[1091,1181,1528,1554]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
(at metacoxae level); humeral width: 
<quantity box="[338,432,1565,1591]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
; maximal height: 
<quantity box="[645,751,1565,1591]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="1.05">1.05 mm</quantity>
(at metacoxae level); lenght/height: 
<number box="[1185,1240,1565,1591]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.76">2.76</number>
; length/maximal width-humeral width: 
<number box="[413,468,1602,1628]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="9.66">9.66</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1266,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis box="[197,387,1640,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Form and Color</emphasis>
. General body form rather sturdy, oval, weakly convex, widened progressively from head up to the middle of elytra (
<figureCitation box="[483,556,1677,1703]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 2" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1054,1078]" captionTargetBox="[318,1288,422,1015]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[290,1296,421,1029]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 2. Dorsal habitus: 1) Berosus degallieri (3.3 mm long); 2) Berosus spiniger (6.6 mm long)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195948/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[541,556,1677,1703]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Dorsal surface testaceous with extensive black areas without metallic sheen, rather shiny except on clypeus; black areas wide on labrum, in the form of a median and longitudinal band on clypeus, in the shape of a broad U on frons, shaded off on pronotal disc; black spots clearly defined on the basal third of the second elytral interstriae, on the first three interstriae behind the middle of the elytra, on humeral hump of interstria 
<number box="[515,529,1826,1852]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="6.0">6</number>
th and towards the middle of interstriae 
<number box="[1007,1021,1826,1852]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="8.0">8</number>
th, 
<number box="[1060,1074,1826,1852]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="9.0">9</number>
th and 
<number box="[1157,1187,1826,1852]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="10.0">10</number>
th; apical segment of maxillary palps, suture, scutellum, striae except 
<number box="[724,753,1864,1890]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="10.0">10</number>
th, elytral and pronotal punctures also blackened. Ground punctures on head and pronotum rather large and uniform-sized but irregularly spaced in some places, fairly dense (spaced by one up to four times their diameter). Ground punctures more superficial on clypeus. Micropunctures scarce.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis box="[197,268,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Head.</emphasis>
Eyes not very prominent, ocular index OI = 
<number box="[799,850,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="2.95">2.95</number>
[OI = S/ 
<number box="[955,993,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="0.5">0.5</number>
(D-S) where D = width of head and S = minimal distance between eyes in dorsal aspect; OI was used by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stys" box="[980,1123,189,215]" pageId="3" pageNumber="58" refString="Stys, P. (1960) The Czechoslovakian populations of Notonecta reuteri Hungerford. Acta Societas Entomologicae Czechoslovaka, 57, 129 - 135." type="journal article" year="1960">
Stys (
<number box="[1050,1114,189,215]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="1960.0">1960</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for aquatic Heteroptera]. Antenna much longer than maxillary palpi.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1403,838,862]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" targetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1403,838,862]" box="[151,1403,838,862]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,838,862]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">FIGURE 3.</emphasis>
Male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[476,672,839,862]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="degallieri">
<emphasis box="[476,672,839,862]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Berosus degallieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption box="[151,1410,1485,1509]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195950/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" targetBox="[165,1420,916,1441]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1410,1485,1509]" box="[151,1410,1485,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,308,1485,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">FIGURE 4–6.</emphasis>
Ventral details of 
<taxonomicName box="[503,698,1486,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="degallieri">
<emphasis box="[503,698,1486,1509]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Berosus degallieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 4) Mesosternal process,; 5) Metasternal process; 6) Fifth ventrite.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1551,2025]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,152,1148]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="55" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis box="[197,292,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum with lateral angles rounded, posterior ones more widely. Scutellum punctate on its periphery. Elytra with ten fine striae, the first seven ones well impressed; punctures on striae spaced by 
<number box="[1368,1436,1588,1614]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1 to 3</number>
times their own width, set most close together along inner striae, and hardly larger than those on pronotum. Interstriae broad and flat, with punctures forming rather irregular rows, sometimes two or three in number, a little finer than those of striae. Micropunctures on interstriae, chiefly inner ones, rare and very light. Scutellar stria with eight punctures. Systematic punctures larger on interstriae 
<number box="[975,989,1737,1763]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
rd, 
<number box="[1031,1044,1737,1763]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
th and 
<number box="[1128,1143,1737,1763]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="7.0">7</number>
th. Sutural angle of each elytron narrowly rounded. No spine-like hairs on outer interstriae. Long hairs on interstriae 
<number box="[1243,1254,1775,1801]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="1.0">1</number>
st, 
<number box="[1293,1306,1775,1801]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
rd, 
<number box="[1347,1360,1775,1801]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
th and 
<number box="[151,179,1812,1838]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="11.0">11</number>
th. Ventral surface glossy, pubescent, mostly punctate, blackened except labium and prosternum testaceous. Mesosternal process laminar with a strong tooth pointing downwards, followed by a low and irregular ridge and ending in rounded angle (
<figureCitation box="[506,580,1887,1913]" captionStart="FIGURE 4 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox="[165,1420,916,1441]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,882,1474]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4 – 6. Ventral details of Berosus degallieri. 4) Mesosternal process,; 5) Metasternal process; 6) Fifth ventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195950/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[562,580,1887,1913]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). Metasternal process triangular and almost flat, with the postero-lateral angles not raised and produced into a rather strong obtuse angle (
<figureCitation box="[939,1012,1924,1950]" captionStart="FIGURE 4 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox="[165,1420,916,1441]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,882,1474]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4 – 6. Ventral details of Berosus degallieri. 4) Mesosternal process,; 5) Metasternal process; 6) Fifth ventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195950/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[995,1012,1924,1950]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Posterior angle forming a narrow keel, broadly rounded in lateral aspect and strongly raised above the postero-lateral angles. Legs testaceous except pubescent and blackish part of femora. Femoral pubescence (male) covering nearly 
<number box="[1243,1274,1999,2025]" pageId="3" pageNumber="54" value="80.0">80</number>
% of the hind and 
<number box="[203,234,152,178]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="70.0">70</number>
% of the middle femora. Male protarsi with expanded pads on the two basal segments; all protarsal segments, including the apical one, weakly swollen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis box="[197,320,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Lateral edges of ventrites smooth, the first ventrite without lateral depressions and with a median carina gradually depressed towards the posterior edge. Apical notch of fifth ventrite rather broad with its lateral edges converging backwards and its bottom strongly bidentate (
<figureCitation box="[1058,1135,301,327]" captionStart="FIGURE 4 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox="[165,1420,916,1441]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,882,1474]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4 – 6. Ventral details of Berosus degallieri. 4) Mesosternal process,; 5) Metasternal process; 6) Fifth ventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195950/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[1117,1135,301,327]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1352,1426,301,327]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,838,862]" captionTargetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[488,1100,309,815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Berosus degallieri (0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[1411,1426,301,327]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
) subcylindrical and rather thick, ventral face straight and dorsal face strongly convex in lateral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1406,338,364]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,838,862]" captionTargetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[488,1100,309,815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Berosus degallieri (0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[1391,1406,338,364]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
a), distal part beyond basal piece very narrow in dorsal and ventral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[1024,1097,376,402]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,838,862]" captionTargetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[488,1100,309,815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Berosus degallieri (0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[1082,1097,376,402]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
b,c). Total length: 
<quantity box="[1321,1432,376,402]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="0.78">0.78 mm</quantity>
, basal piece representing three-quarters of it. Parameres very strongly bent in their terminal part, with apex curved towards ventral face (
<figureCitation box="[491,560,450,476]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,838,862]" captionTargetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[488,1100,309,815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Berosus degallieri (0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[545,560,450,476]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
a). Median lobe almost as long as parameres. Part of parameres beyond the basal piece dilated towards ventral face.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,321,525,551]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Variation.</emphasis>
Allotype: total length: 
<quantity box="[609,705,525,551]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
; maximal width: 
<quantity box="[919,1015,525,551]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
; humeral width: 
<quantity box="[1222,1318,525,551]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
; maximal height: 
<quantity box="[241,314,562,588]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
; length/height: 
<number box="[498,538,562,588]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.3">3.3</number>
; length/maximal width-humeral width: 
<number box="[1009,1040,562,588]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="11.0">11</number>
. General female body form more elongated and depressed than for the male. Protarsi without expanded pads and not swollen; apical segment one third thinner than in male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,674,700]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Discussion.</emphasis>
As shown in Table 
<number box="[574,589,674,700]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="1.0">1</number>
, three species combine a blackened clypeus, a metasternal process with a posterior angle higher than the postero-lateral angles, and an apical notch of the fifth ventrite with a bifid tooth: 
<taxonomicName box="[229,379,749,774]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="degallieri" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[229,379,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. degallieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[388,454,749,775]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Queney, 2006" authorityName="Queney" authorityYear="2006" box="[468,810,749,775]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guyanensis">
<emphasis box="[468,635,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. guyanensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Queney" box="[643,810,749,775]" pageId="4" pageNumber="58" refString="Queney, P. (2006) Description de trois especes nouvelles de Berosus de Guyane francaise (Coleoptera, Hydrophilidae). Bulletin de la Societe entomologique de France 111, 457 - 464." type="journal article" year="2006">
Queney, 
<number box="[750,810,749,775]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Knisch, 1921" authorityName="Knisch" authorityYear="1921" box="[869,1170,749,775]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrinus">
<emphasis box="[869,1003,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. nigrinus</emphasis>
Knisch, 
<number box="[1111,1170,749,775]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="1921.0">1921</number>
</taxonomicName>
but the last one is the only one to have its dorsal face entirely blackened. The first two species can be separated by their metasternal process with the postero-angles, nearly acute and very strongly produced in 
<taxonomicName box="[1038,1200,824,849]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guyanensis">
<emphasis box="[1038,1200,824,849]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. guyanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, hardly produced in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,303,861,886]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="degallieri">
<emphasis box="[151,303,861,886]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. degallieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[321,396,861,887]" captionStart="FIGURE 4 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox="[165,1420,916,1441]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,882,1474]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4 – 6. Ventral details of Berosus degallieri. 4) Mesosternal process,; 5) Metasternal process; 6) Fifth ventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195950/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[379,396,861,887]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Males are easily differentiated by examination of the genitalia: the distal pieces are spindle-shaped in ventral aspect in 
<taxonomicName box="[581,750,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guyanensis">
<emphasis box="[581,750,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. guyanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but flat and parallel in 
<taxonomicName box="[1045,1198,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="degallieri">
<emphasis box="[1045,1198,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. degallieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the parameres and median lobe are about the same length in 
<taxonomicName box="[652,802,936,961]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="degallieri">
<emphasis box="[652,802,936,961]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. degallieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[819,891,936,962]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,255,838,862]" captionTargetBox="[489,1082,321,800]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[488,1100,309,815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Berosus degallieri (0.78 mm long), a) lateral aspect; b) dorsal aspect; c) ventral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195949/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[875,891,936,962]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), but much longer than the median lobe in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Berosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guyanensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">B. guyanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,1010,1036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for Nicolas Dégallier, an eminent French entomologist and specialist on the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,274,1048,1074]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Histeridae</taxonomicName>
, who collected the two 
<typeStatus box="[551,613,1048,1074]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">types</typeStatus>
of the new species described here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,1085,1111]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is only known from 
<collectingCountry box="[767,858,1085,1111]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Brasilia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[875,950,1085,1111]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Brazil</collectingCountry>
) where it was collected at a light-trap in &quot;Cerrado&quot;.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
